links.slidetitle: Academic Support Programs that May Be Right for You
links.displaytext: Academic Support Programs that May Be Right for You

slidetranscripts.Text: Welcome to HCCs Early Alert Tutorial for Students. If you have been instructed to complete this module, your class or classes are participating in the early alert program this semester. To view this module, click the Next button in the lower right hand corner at the conclusion of each slide. You may also select a topic from the navigation pane on the left.

The College is committed to providing support when you need it. Through the Starfish Early Alert system, instructors and advisors are able to communicate and provide immediate help at the first sign of a problem or commend you when you are doing well in a course. In addition, our early alert program provides you with direct access to the people and services available to help you.

Throughout the semester, you may receive Starfish notices in your HCC Email indicating your current academic progress. These notifications are intended to provide you with early feedback to successfully pass your course. If you receive a notification, please contact the appropriate instructor and/or advisor listed in the email. If you do not receive a notification, then you are likely to be on track for success.

There are two ways to access the Starfish system. The first way is through your Canvas site. Once you have logged onto your Canvas page, click on the Early Alert link on the navigation pane on the left side of the Canvas page. Be sure that you are accessing your Canvas page through the latest versions of Firefox, Chrome or Safari.

A second way to access the HCC Early Alert program is through the URL login https://howardcc.edu/starfish. Enter your username, which is the same as myHCC: first initial, first seven characters of your last name, and last four digits of your student ID number. Your password is also the same as myHCC. If you are still having trouble with your password and/or with your HCC email account, call Help Desk at 443-518-4444.

The first step to using the Starfish Early Alert system is to set up your profile. Click on your name at the top right corner of the Home page to view or edit your profile. Confirm or correct your cell and home phone numbers. In Alternate Email, enter the email address for your cell phone. Next to mobile Users, click the more information icon for a list of common carriers and email address formats. For Send my correspondence: click the Both button. Upload a photo if you like to personalize your page. To upload a photo click on the Upload Photo link. Browse for a photo from your files. Recommended file formats are JPEG, GIF, and PNG. Click the Upload Now button. Click the Submit button to save your updates. [Make this a simulation slide.] Click the Resources button to view directions for setting up your profile.

The next step is to routinely check your HCC email account for notifications and your cell phone for texts from Starfish. It is important to check your HCC email on a daily basis since Howard Community College recognizes HCC email as the official method of communication with students. To receive texts, you must set it up as an alternate email in your profile. Your instructors raise alerts approximately three times a semester. It is important to note that your Canvas inbox and HCC email are two separate accounts.

The HCC Early Alert Program has several types of alerts. You may receive alerts that flag you for Attendance Concern, Late/Missing assignments, Low Academic Performance or In Danger of Failing. If you receive one or more of these flag alerts, review your exam and assignment grades, and check your class syllabus. You may also receive a kudos alert from your instructor. The kudos alert lets you know that your current academic performance is leading to success in the class.

If you should receive a flag, talk to your instructor about what you need to do to successfully complete the course. Secondly, talk to Completion Services staff or your cohort advisor about an action plan and supports you can access in order to successfully complete the course.

No two students are exactly the same and no two students need exactly the same support. Your chances for success improve greatly when you use the academic supports and resources available to you. In the next few slides, youll learn about a variety of different resources that are available to support your pathway at Howard Community College.

You are here because you are interested and willing to learn new things but you might need further information or support along the way. Howard Community College provides a large number of services and resources. Click each image on this slide to learn about just a few of them.

Here are some additional services to assist you as a student at HCC. Click each image to learn more.

The complete list of services may also be viewed on the Starfish home page under the tab services. Talk to your instructor, a completion specialist and/or your advisor about what services or resources are most suitable to your needs.

The Learning Assistance Center, referred to as the LAC, is located in RCF 340 across from the Test Center. The LAC phone number is 443-518-1320. The center provides study skills workshops & math reviews, scheduled tutoring, drop-in tutoring, online writing assistance, math video tutorials, and computer aided tutorials. All services are free to students!

Amy: Click the pictures to view other resource centers and labs.

Then click Next to continue.

The ESL Pronunciation Lab is located in DH 210.

It is available for HCC students enrolled in any credit class and for non-native speakers

The ESL Pronunciation Lab provides individualized practice in Pronunciation, Presentation Skills, Academic Discussion Skills, and Interview Skills.

The Composition & Literature Center (CLC) is located in DH 210 and provides individualized instruction for all HCC students enrolled in an English course. Tutoring in the CLC is offered on a walk-in basis

Composition & Literature Center (CLC) Duncan Hall 210

Provides individualized instruction for all HCC students enrolled in an English course

Tutoring in the CLC is offered on a walk-in basis

The Math Center (MAC) is located in Hickory Ridge 230.

It is open to all HCC students currently enrolled in a Mathematics class

Computer software is available for all math courses and free tutoring is offered by faculty and student tutors

The Open Accounting Lab is located in DH 310 and is manned by instructors and peer leaders.

The Open Accounting Lab allows students to study for exams alone or with other students and provides help with homework or specific problems or concepts.

Instructors and/or peer mentors are available to answer questions for students.

HCC also has academic support programs that may be right for you! Click each image to learn more about each of them.

Career Links is designed to assist HCC students who are low-income single parents or displaced homemakers identify and access resources necessary for success. Howard P.R.I.D.E is a leadership program that encourages the continued academic, professional and personal development of black and minority males. Step UP is a program that helps students connect and succeed at HCC by pairing them with a faculty or staff coach for on-on-one support to assist with the challenges of college and life.

Ambiciones provides support to Hispanic/Latino students by connecting them to resources on campus such as academic advising and tutoring, mentoring and coaching, and personal and career counseling. Student Support Services is a federally funded TRIO program that provides academic enhancement services to students who are first generation college studens, Pell Grant eligible and/or have a documented disability. The Veterans Affairs staff work with veterans and their qualified dependents to initiate processes necessary to activate and maintain their benefits.

If you have any questions or concerns during the semester, contact the following. For password and computer help, contact Help Desk at 443-518-4444. For questions about a flag, current grade or assignments, check Canvas and/or contact your instructor. For questions about the HCC Early Alert Program and how to access resources on campus, contact Completion Services at 443-518-1320.
That concludes this module. If youd like to repeat any of the information in the module, please use the navigation pane on the left hand side to click on the topic youd like to review.
